Exploring Popularity in Music: A Capstone

Stephanie Sears

8/16/2019

Introduction

As an Assistant Professor researching and teaching in a Historically Black College and University (HBCU) that offers educational curriculum in liberarl arts and the humanities, I primarily conduct qualitative research. Situated in the academic disciplines of Africana Womens Studies, Religion and Psychology, I am interested in womens experiences in society, the religious/spiritual dimensions of everyday experiences, and the psychological consciousness motivating everyday human behavior. My research interests compel me to ask questions about meaning. I am always seeking novel ways to understand and interpret the reasons behind why people do what they do. Thus, my engagement with data science is rooted in my intellectual curiosity to derive meaning from patterns of behavior.

Part of the objective of this capstone project is to demonstrate the usefulness of data science in qualitative studies. Very often, social science research integrates qualitative and quantitative methods to provide a fuller description of a phenomenon. Data science represents an ideal approach in this endeavor, enabling me to analyze unstructured, subjective data (a common source of data in qualitative studies) and potentially replicable or generalizable data (a common research requirement in quantitative studies). Overall, my aim is to analyze and explain narrative associated with numbers!

This capstone project is a text mining and sentiment analysis study. It focuses on the R&B music of Patti LaBelle, Whitney Houston and Mariah Carey. By analyzing social media comments, this project seeks to discover descriptive themes pertinent to popular African American Women R&B singers. Given the salience of the idea of the diva, this project seeks to uncover how audiences identify with the top divas of R&B and the ways in which their interactivity with media constructs notions of the popular. It uses data science to understand the audiences interactive behavior that correlates to popularity and aims to build a self-consistent explanation or model that might interpret that behavior.

Conceptual Background

With the advent of social media metrics such as likes, follows, pins, shares, comments, and views, the everyday connoisseur of culture enjoys a greater stake in the social construction of value. Indeed, cultivating fandom, an effect of the ease in which audiences now express belonging and non-belonging through mediated platforms, is currently a cultural practice. Its prevalence has transformed how people interact and intersect with popular culture. As it is now possible to become a career influencer utilizing social media platforms, it is of profound interest to researchers to examine the ways in which cultural consciousness defines whats valuable and how such definitions gain considerable social force.

That an influential social force is garnering strength through mediated platforms is no new phenomenon. But the growing importance of popular culture as a context of public persuasion is compelling. In such a context, we witness the transformation of popular expression into impactful commentary that can either launch a public figure into stardom or topple an embattled icon, ensuring a purposively shameful fall from grace. Once relegated a marginal influence, popular culture has became an integral force in the socialization of collective consciousness. As a result, the everyday person participates in the curating of the collective self-image. A vote cast (as a like, a share, or a follow, etc) represents, in many ways, a statement about the collective self-image of society and how social actors want to see themselves evaluated within it.

For example, religious scholar, Robin Sylvan (2002) explores the ways in which popular culture has morphed into a religious phenomenon, particularly as experienced through popular music. He writes,

Observers of culture and scholars of religion have said many things about the slow decline of religion and the death of God in Western civilization.[R]eligion and God are not dead, but very much alive and well and dancing to the beat of popular music; the religious impulse has simply migrated to another sector of the culture, a sector in which religious sensibilities have flourished and made an enormous impact on a large portion of the population.Yet, because conventional wisdom has taught us to regard popular music as trivial forms of secular entertainment, these religious dimensions remain hidden from view, marginalized and misunderstood (p.3).

Sylvan seeks to make explicit the ways in which popular contexts reveal hidden examples of contemporary religiosity. As a result, he raises the value of the notion of the popular. As contemporary folks elect a popular, they raise new deity forms as well (the popularized one becomes a symbolic totem of the collective self-image). In addition, they reconstitute notions of the sacred and ritual (by casting a vote for whats deemed MOST valued) and by ritualizing these new notions through new traditions of sharing and memorializing.

Research Problem and Significance

Data science offers an exciting possibility to test the relationship between social media user activity and socio-cultural definitions about value. Given Sylvans claim that popular culture co-creates new forms of divinity, the construct of popularity is in need of examination. I am interested in exploring popularity in the context of womens influence (Patti LaBelle, Whitney Houston and Mariah Carey), music (R&B music), religion/spiritual experience (the electing of the popular diva or divine one through liking, viewing, and commenting) and psychological consciousness (the deep meaning behind the activity that reveals implicit themes and unconscious motives). Without understanding the ways in which social media users create data, these new forms of value remain hidden. Equally true, without proper attention to this phenomenon, it is likely that unintended psycho-spiritual (and unconscious) consequences remained unexamined as well.

This capstone examines comments on YouTube to understand sentiment and public perception of popularity. It seeks to transform words (YouTube comments) into variables. These variables, in turn, can be employed in unsupervised machine learning tasks utilized to understand textual data. As such, this project is interested in natural language processing in order to derive meaning from YouTube users comments and participatory activity on select YouTube videos. Framing the main question within this methodological context, my research question is: What is the relationship between social media user activity and popularity? How do sentiments communicate social value? The answers to these questions can help to advance a qualitative interpretive framework by which to understand the dynamic behavior of individuals and groups in their attempt to encourage and/or frustrate the creation of a social icon reflective of the collective self-image.

Comments Data

The comments dataset, saved to a data frame entitled all_comments, contains 30402 observations representing user commentary on the videos of Patti LaBelle, Whitney Houston, and Mariah Carey. The key variables of this dataset are the commentary text and the video identification numbers associated with the video from which the comments are drawn.

Video Statistics Data

The video statistics data, saved to a data frame entitled videostats, contains 111 observations of 7 variables. These variables are date, title of video, view count, like count, dislike count, comment count and a created metric to measure popularity. In order to devise a popularity metric, this project uses the simple equation of views + likes + comments - dislikes. The videostats numerical data was normalized in order to have a consistent standard of comparison across the data.

Code to get video statistics:

videostats1 <-

  )

Data Wrangling

To prepare the data for analysis, some cleaning was in order. I used the text mining package, TM, the package, Textclean, and the package, Stringr, to assist with helpful data cleaning functions for text analytics. Dates were converted to actual dates, factor data was converted back into numeric data and data was normalized. In addition, specifc data was stored in one data frame to prepare it for analysis in R.

Code for initial data cleaning for the videos data:

videosPat <-

Code to get comments data into one data frame:

all_comments <- data.frame(comment = character(),
                           video_id = character(),
                           stringsAsFactors = FALSE)
j <- 1
comments <- c(comments1, comments2, comments3)
for (i in 1:length(comments)) {
   if (length(as.character(comments[[i]][["textDisplay"]])) > 0) {
    all_comments[j:(j + length(as.character(comments[[i]][["textDisplay"]])) - 1), "comment"] <- 
      as.character(comments[[i]][["textDisplay"]])
    all_comments[j:(j + length(as.character(comments[[i]][["textDisplay"]])) - 1), "video_id"] <- 
      as.character(comments[[i]][["videoId"]])
       j <- j + length(as.character(comments[[i]][["textDisplay"]]))
  }

}

Additional clean up of the comments data allows for the removal of stop words and punctuation as well as converting text to lowercase.

remove_words <- 
  c("can", "she", "shes", "can", "rip")
all_comments_clean <-
  all_comments$comment %>%
  as.data.frame() %>%
  rename(comment = names(.)[1]) %>%
  mutate(comment = replace_non_ascii(comment)) %>%
  mutate(comment = tolower(comment)) %>%
  mutate(comment = removePunctuation(comment)) %>%
  mutate(comment = str_replace_all(comment, pattern = "[0-9]*", replacement = "")) %>%
  mutate(comment = gsub("[^0-9A-Za-z///' ]","'" , comment)) %>%
  mutate(comment = gsub("''","" , comment)) %>%
  mutate(comment = str_replace_all(comment, pattern = "/n", replacement = "")) %>%
  mutate(comment = str_replace_all(comment, pattern = "/", replacement = "")) %>%
  mutate(comment = gsub(pattern = "br", replacement = "", comment)) %>%
  mutate(comment = gsub(pattern = " +", replacement = " ", comment)) %>%
  mutate(comment = removeWords(comment, stopwords())) %>%
  mutate(comment = removeWords(comment, remove_words)) %>%
  mutate(video_id = all_comments$video_id) %>%
  filter(nchar(comment) > 1)
word_freq_Whit <-
  all_comments_clean %>%
  filter(video_id %in% videosWhit$video_id) %>%
  select(comment) %>%
  as.character() %>%
  termFreq()
word_freq_Mar <-
  all_comments_clean %>%
  filter(video_id %in% videosMar$video_id) %>%
  select(comment) %>%
  as.character() %>%
  termFreq()
word_freq_Pat <-
  all_comments_clean %>%
  filter(video_id %in% videosPat$video_id) %>%
  select(comment) %>%
  as.character() %>%
  termFreq()

Code to clean up videostats data and to get videostats data into one data frame:

videostats$title <- 
  c(as.character(videos1$title), as.character(videos2$title), as.character(videos3$title))
videostats$date <- 
  c(as.character(videos1$publishedAt), as.character(videos2$publishedAt), as.character(videos3$publishedAt))

videostats <-
  videostats %>%
  select(date, title, viewCount, likeCount, dislikeCount, commentCount) %>%
  as.tibble() %>%
  mutate(date = as.Date(substr(date, 1, 10))) %>%
  mutate(viewCount = as.numeric(as.character(viewCount)),
         likeCount = as.numeric(as.character(likeCount)),
         dislikeCount = as.numeric(as.character(dislikeCount)),
         commentCount = as.numeric(as.character(commentCount))) %>%
  mutate(viewCount = viewCount / mean(viewCount, na.rm = TRUE)) %>%
  mutate(likeCount = likeCount / mean(likeCount, na.rm = TRUE)) %>%
  mutate(dislikeCount = dislikeCount / mean(dislikeCount, na.rm = TRUE)) %>%
  mutate(commentCount = commentCount / mean(commentCount, na.rm = TRUE)) %>%
  mutate(pop_score = viewCount + likeCount + commentCount - dislikeCount)

Exploratory Data Analysis

Preliminary explorations of the data reveals linear relationships between the number of views and likes, dislikes, and commentary (see plots below). An examination of the relationship between commenting activity and popularity suggests that the more popular an artist is, the more likely it is to have commenting on their videos. Could it be that the active commenting on the videos actually contributes to the notion of popularity? In other words, are active fans constructing an ever-increasing idea of whats popular by way of their ongoing activity? Further exploration of the data will seek to delve further into this possibility.

Plots examining these relationships:

p1 <- 
  ggplot(data = videostats) + 
  geom_point(aes(x = viewCount, y = likeCount))
p2 <- 
  ggplot(data = videostats) + 
  geom_point(aes(x = viewCount, y = dislikeCount))
p3 <- 
  ggplot(data = videostats) + 
  geom_point(aes(x = viewCount, y = commentCount))
grid.arrange(p1, p2, p3, ncol = 2)

These plots show how likes, dislikes, and comments relate to the number of views. Each plot shows that there is a positive linear relationship between each of the variables and views. In each of the plots there is an outlier, which will require further exploration. However, there is a degree of consistency among the three plots, with much of user response concentrated around the smaller increments of views. As views increase, liking, disliking and commenting activity seems to cease.

Since the the distribution between commentCount and viewCount appears to have more nonlinearity, I thought it would be interesting to see what patterns emerge between comments and the pop_score. The plot appears as follows:

p4 <- 
  ggplot(data = videostats) + 
  geom_point(aes(x = pop_score, y = commentCount))
print(p4)

Deeper Dive into the Data: Language Processing

In natural language processing, one of the objectives is to understand the interaction between human actors and the virtual platforms/computers used to capture it. In this project, I am interested in understanding the meaning introjected into the popularity of LaBelle, Houston and Carey more deeply by users of YouTube. By examining the comments, I am looking for meaningful information that might help flesh out the subjective experience of YouTube users in relationship to the stars they love and admire.

To help extract the meaningful information, I created a word cloud from users comments for each artist. Word clouds represent an efficient way to visualize the most important terms, based on word frequency. A close examination of the results of word clouds reveal attributes of the text not easily apparent by simply reading the comments text data itself.

Topic Modeling

As a useful correlate to the word clouds, topic modeling was used. By examining word frequency and visualizing a hierarchical ordering of the words used in comments, it is possible to interpret how much weight to give certain terms over and against others. This information further helps provide context for the terms that appear in the word clouds.

Patti LaBelle Topics

tidy_comments_Pat <- 
  word_freq_Pat %>%
  as.data.frame() %>%
  rename(count = names(.)[1]) %>%
  cbind(words = names(word_freq_Pat)) %>%
  mutate(words = as.character(words)) %>%
  mutate(id = seq(1, length(words))) %>%
  filter(regexpr("patti", words) == -1) %>%
  filter(regexpr("labelle", words) == -1)
rownames(tidy_comments_Pat) <- NULL
tidy_dtm_Pat <- cast_dtm(tidy_comments_Pat, words, id, count)
lda_Pat <- 
  LDA(tidy_dtm_Pat, k = 3) %>%
  tidy() %>%
  group_by(topic) %>%
  top_n(10, beta) %>%
  ungroup() %>%
  arrange(topic, -beta)
lda_Pat %>%
  mutate(term = tidy_comments_Pat[match(term, tidy_comments_Pat$id), "words"]) %>%
  mutate(term = reorder(term, beta)) %>%
  ggplot(aes(term, beta, fill = factor(topic))) +
  geom_col(show.legend = FALSE) +
  facet_wrap(~ topic, scales = "free") +
  labs(title = "Patti Labelle Topics") +
  coord_flip()

Sentiment Analysis

In addition to exploring word clouds, this project takes advantage of predefined lexicon dictionaries using the R packages tidytext and textdata. Sentiment analysis aims to determine the opinion and subjective impression of particular texts. By employing sentiment analysis, I am able to calculate a sentiment score for each artist. This score will provide a useful point of reference for later triangulation with the results of topic modeling. This project uses word-level sentiment analysis.

Patti LaBelle Sentiment Analysis

tokensPat <-
  unnest_tokens(all_comments_clean %>% filter(video_id %in% videosPat$video_id), word, comment)
sentiment_Pat <-
  tokensPat %>%
  inner_join(get_sentiments("loughran")) %>% # pull out only sentiment words
  count(sentiment) %>% # count the # of positive & negative words
  spread(sentiment, n, fill = 0) %>% # made data wide rather than narrow
  mutate(sentiment = 100 * (positive - negative) / (positive + negative))

Discussion

For this project, I really wanted to understand the ways in which fans constructed the popular by way of their active social media behavior. The above data exploration provides a snapshot into the interactive and interpretive nature of fan bases. It is through the exploration of actual users comments that a model of popularity and its associated emotional impressions emerge.

Word Clouds

In all of the word clouds for the three artists, there is an overlap in the representation of terms like: song, amazing, beautiful, sing, voice, and love. This overlap in terms certainly suggest that fans require beautiful singing voices and a love for both the songs and quality of the singing for an artist to be considered popular. However, one might assume this is the case: we didnt need data science to tell us that. Rather, we desire for data science to offer us insights we perhaps would have never considered previously. Therefore, word clouds are the most helpful if we shift our gaze to note the occurrences of unique and unusual terms.

In Patti LaBelles word cloud, some of the words that stand out are: big, world, soul, god, hair, years and time. These terms seem to point to something timeless about a popular artist, perhaps suggesting a quality that is big or beyond this world. Of course, the term big could be associated with hair as Patti LaBelle was known to don especially big 1980s hair styles. Even though this detail may seem trivial, perhaps it is a significant feature for predicting fan-based measures of popularity. Many celebrities sport a signature style and become well-known for their carefully cultivated look. That such an attribute registers in the minds of fans indicates the multi-dimensional appraisal processes that occur and that popularity of singers is not solely about how the voice sounds. However, big could also represent the perceived bigness of Patti, herself, in terms of status and her long running career in music. The terms, time and years certainly point to longevity. However, what is most striking in Pattis word cloud is the term god, which recalls the introduction of my project and its concern with the ways in which audience members construct the divine (here, understood as the diva). Perhaps big is connected to the term god and, if so, popularity, as measured by the commenting behavior of YouTube users, comes to mean something beyond mere human experiencesomething that is greater and more awesome in nature.

In Whitney Houstons word cloud, some of the more intriguing terms that stand out are: jesus, angel, sweet, peace, pray, earth, heaven and blessed. Similar to the word cloud for Patti LaBelle, Whitneys word cloud seems to be associated with otherworldly terms. However, Whitneys words seem to be qualitatively different from Pattis. Theres a softer edge to the terms, pointing more towards how Whitney makes the audience FEEL, perhaps even, inside themselves. Perhaps audiences feel at peace, or if they had been visited by an angel, or even blessed. Or, perhaps, these terms may signify that they think Whitney, herself, is an angel and that Whitney is blessed. In any event, popularity comes to again mean something that is transcendent. Yet, these terms can also be said to be pointing to something that is equally as immanentthe term earth appears, perhaps bringing the notion of the angelic to the earth realm, perhaps even implying that Whitney, herself, is down to earth. In this interpretation, it would seem that audiences appreciate the type of popularity that seems larger than life on one level but all the more assessible on another level. Perhaps the popular are indeed the earth angels.

Finally, in Mariah Careys word cloud, some of the unique terms are: legend, christmas, top, queen, and hot. The word god also appears in Mariahs word cloud, but unlike the soul-inflected language of both Pattis and Whitneys word clouds, the themes in Mariahs word cloud seem to point less toward the otherworldly and more toward the physical and material reality permeating and surrounding Mariahs work. The terms, legend and christmas might be associated as Mariah is known to create new trends that have staying power, as in being one of only a handful of popular artists to record a christmas song that enjoys yearly plays alongside other legendary holiday classics. The term top stands out because while it points to something hierarchical, it does not necessarily have to point to something as high as the gods. The term hot could refer to Mariahs music, sound or looks. It is an interesting term in this context because even as Mariah seems to be more of this world she is still a luminary. And, just as the sun, our highest luminary in the sky, is close enough to be considered in this world, (in the same way that queens are in this world) one still ought not to get too close, lest one gets burned by its heat. So, the word cloud seems to point to a definition of popularity that is intimate even as it is shrouded in an aura that demands audiences keep their distance.

Topic Modeling

The previous discussion of the word clouds reveals some compelling associations however, interpreting word clouds is an imprecise exercise. For this reason, triangulating the interpretions of the word clouds with topic modeling provides another layer of analysis. Topic analysis returns clusters of similar terms and interpreting the possible meaning behind the clusters is the chief objective of topic modeling. For the purposes of this project, there are 3 topics per artist.

Patti LaBelles topics, particularly topic 1, seem to point to Pattis timelessnessperhaps in the sense of her never-ending career or that she remains the best. These notions correlate well with the word cloud. Whitney Houstons topics seem to point to the audiences overall fondness for Whitney, with love being the most important term in topic 1. The comments also point to the audience missing Whitney (an important theme that also shows up in the sentiment analysis). Thus, perhaps the notion gleaned from the word cloud that Whitney is perceived as an earth angel can be linked to the fact of her untimely death and the audiences ongoing relationship with her through her music. Finally, Mariah Careys topics seem to cohere with what is hinted in the word cloud. Mariahs topics seem to be related to the business side of musical lifebuying and registering music, for example. These are still very important aspects of popularityof course, fans also vote for value with their wallets!

Overall, it would seem that there is some level of synergy between the outputs of the word clouds and the topic models.

Sentiment Analysis

In this project, a final layer of analysis was to calculate a sentiment score to discern just what audiences love (or not) about the popular. Using the lexicon library, positive, negative, uncertainty, litigious and constraining tones in text are counted. From this initial set of sentiment categories, a sentiment store was calculated (positive - negative/positive + negative). Patti LaBelles sentiment score is 42.7, Whitney Houstons score is 2.29 and Mariah Careys score is 58.5. This is very interesting results! It would seem at first glance that Whitney Houston is not as popular as Patti LaBelle and Mariah Carey after all!

However, we know that cant be true (as evidenced by the word cloud and topic models). A closer examination of the number of positive and negative comments reveal an important nuance. For Patti LaBelle and Mariah Carey, there is a greater difference between the number of positive and negative comments, with there being more positive than negative comments. However, for Whitney Houston, there are nearly equal in number negative and positive comments. Cross-referencing this data with the topic modeling reveals that many of the negative commenting is in reference to audience reactions to Whitneys death. Many comments convey sadness over missing Whitney. Thus, here is an important occasion where context figures prominently to explain the numbers. In this case, negative comments do not point to less popularity; perhaps the presence of negative comments, in this case, conveys stronger emotional resonancea phenomenon which seems to match the impressions offered by the word cloud. Therefore, negative sentimentality is not necessarily a bad thing. In fact, this project shows that strong feeling, whether negative or positive, is a salient indicator of popularity.

Conclusion

This study was interested in discerning the relationship between social media users activity and notions of popularity which point to contemporary conceptualizations of the sacred. In particular, this project is grounded on the assumption that music audiences, for instance, play an active and dynamic role in the cultivation of contemporary expression of sacredness through their social media commenting. Employing Robin Sylvans view that popular music contains within it intense religious significance understood in the context of audiences emotional experiences, this project uses data science to explore the confluence of popularity, perceived value, sacred/religious themes and sentiment. What is fascinating in the results of this study is that text mining and sentiment analysis seems to confirm Sylvans claims through the various references to God, soul, heaven, angels, etc.

In sum, popularity seems to boil down to three qualities:

  1. it contains bigness and timelessness (it expands the sense of the ordinary)
  2. it is both transcendent and immanent (it reaches beyond and within human beings)
  3. it is reflective of legendary status within the contemporary world (it is set apart)

Interestingly enough, these three qualities might have been used to describe any number of significant religious leaders for whom many of the worlds religions are named. The fact that these qualities have been gleaned from word clouds, topic models and sentiment scores for three female R&B singers reveals the ongoing desire for the human heart to be connected with these ideals. The realization of the emotional importance of connection to these values is evidenced by the intensity of sorrow and grief when this contact is somehow severed (as in the example of audiences who miss and mourn Whitney Houston in her untimely death.) What this project ultimately shows is that people are motivated to act toward their highest values and to select symbolic representations of such values from within the cultural milieu. Because of the emotional signficance of selecting a symbol of ones sacred, it would seem that commenting, liking, sharing, and similar activities should be understood not as trivial distractions but rather as a contemporary meaning-making system of great import.

Limitations of the Project

While this project attempts to discern the relationship between commenting behavior and popularity associated with Patti LaBelle, Whitney Houston, and Mariah Carey, it comes with several limitations. The first limitation involves my use of the Tuber package itself. The Tuber package is great for pulling data from YouTube. However, in its current form, my dataset includes all the videos posted on a particular channel. The code I employed to create the dataset casted a wide net, including some video content that is not relevant to my specific research question. While I believe the data is rich, it is not perfect. Filtering the videos on the channel id proved to be beyond the scope of this current research project. Because of the extra video content, the level of specificity is limited in this project.

Another limitation involves the level of filtering when creating word clouds and topic models. As text mining is not necessarily a precise process, it requires a flexible approach when deciding which terms to remove from consideration. Some of the words returned in the word clouds and topic models did not seem very useful or descriptive. If performed again, I would consider doing several rounds of filtering to ensure that the terms returned in the analysis truly paint a descriptive and relevant story.

As an extension to the last point, using one-word topic modeling comes with some degree of limitation as well. While the one-word topic model is simple and relatively assessible, a multiple-words model might provide more overall contextualization of the themes.

Finally, this project is limited in terms of the balancing of the videos, comments, and statistics returned for each YouTube channel. Because some channels hosted more videos than others and because some videos had more commenting than others, the data returned for each artist lacked symmetry. While adjustments were made in the code to account for this imbalance, perhaps an alternative plan for handling such matters might have been employed.

Implications and Recommendations for Further Research

This project points to the growing importance of text mining and sentiment analysis. As indicated in the above conclusion, data science reveals that social media commenting and interactive behavior might just be more influential and impactful as a meaning-making system than anyone suspects. Of course, marketing and industry firms already understand the importance of harnassing such information in order to match products and services to ideal target audiences. However, this project also points to the ways in which text mining and sentiment analysis can be helpful to public administration, social work, psychological counseling, and religious institutions. As a meaningful tool to gauge and understand peoples behavior, data science offers these institutions an opportunity to assess what people truly value, which then, can be correlated to how people truly feel about themselves in relationship to their deeply held values.

I would recommend to those who wish to conduct similar research of this nature to do the following for even better results:

  1. Have a succinct and well-defined research question.
  2. To create a dataset with specific videos in mind, instead of using an entire YouTube channel.
  3. To delve beyond the one-word topic analysis to provide a richer context surrounding the relevant themes.

In conclusion, the applications for a text mining and sentiment analysis project are endless. Overall, it enables researchers to capture the evolution of thought and emotion of quickly changing human beings as they engage and impact their world.
